The format is so much faster than it was 5 years ago when there was more focus on battlecruiser “everyone do your thing” and less cEDH

Not even faster necessarily (though it is) but more efficient. I remember every blue deck running Thought Reflection 6ish years ago, but now I can’t remember the last time I saw it. People tend to just want to draw and keep moving ahead.

I think at three mana Arena is still efficient enough, but once upon a time that was also maybe your draw. Like that alone. Your black deck ran Arena and maybe Greed, Blue ran a Thought Reflection and a BSZ and you were good to go with two draw sources in the best draw colors

Building terrible Teysa today and I started with Ambition’s Cost, Ancient Craving, Night’s Whisper, Sign in Blood, Read the Bones, Phyrexian Arena, and Necro, and that’s the untuned rough draft. I’ll add more.

It also used to be the kind of format where you could wait until turn four before you did anything. That gave people the time to stockpile cards. Now the format is quicker. Mana curves are decreasing and we aren’t dropping seven-cost spells six turns in a row (which also allowed us to worry less about card density, since we cast fewer spells on average) 
There’s been a big shift to optimize, which I consider good, but which has also reduced an all-star like Phyrena just a smidge.
Yep
You can't really afford to play non-threats. I remember people just throwing in random Theros block uncommons to round out decks, and people just rarely do that anymore. Every slot has a purpose.

I started playing fantasy football in like sixth grade with my friends. By the time I got to college and was still playing it was a radically different game
Drafting players in 1990 meant looking at box scores in USA Today for lineups. You couldn't see scores until Wed because that's when the Monday night came score was in the paper.
By college you could buy magazines with player breakdowns before pre-seaosn started and read articles online
Today your team score updates live online, you get injury updates texted to you, and you can find player evals updated daily even in the off-season.
